theorem
Th9: ((a is  limit_ordinal & ( 0 ) in b) implies ( exp (a,b) ) is  limit_ordinal)
proof
assume A1: (a is  limit_ordinal & ( 0 ) in b);
per cases  by ORDINAL3:8;
suppose a = ( 0 );

hence thesis by A1,ORDINAL4:20;
end;
suppose A2: ( 0 ) in a;

defpred P[ Ordinal ]
 means
(( 0 ) in $1 implies ( exp (a,$1) ) is  limit_ordinal);
A3: P[ ( {} ) ];
A4: (P[ c ] implies P[ ( succ c ) ])
proof
( exp (a,( succ c )) ) = ( a *^ ( exp (a,c) ) ) by ORDINAL2:44;
hence thesis by A1,ORDINAL3:40;
end;
A5: (((c <> ( {} ) & c is  limit_ordinal) & (for b holds (b in c implies P[ b ]))) implies P[ c ])
proof
assume that
A6: (c <> ( {} ) & c is  limit_ordinal)
and
A7: (for b holds (b in c implies P[ b ]));
deffunc F(Ordinal) = ( exp (a,$1) );
consider f such that A8: (( dom f ) = c & (for b holds (b in c implies ( f . b ) = F(b)))) from ORDINAL2:sch 3;
A9: ( exp (a,c) ) = ( lim f ) by A6,A8,ORDINAL2:45;
f is  non-decreasing by A2,A8,CKB23:1;
then ( Union f ) is_limes_of f by A6,A8,CKB21:1;
then A10: ( exp (a,c) ) = ( Union f ) by A9,ORDINAL2:def 10;
(for d holds (d in ( exp (a,c) ) implies ( succ d ) in ( exp (a,c) )))
proof
let d;
assume d in ( exp (a,c) );
then consider b being set such that A11: (b in ( dom f ) & d in ( f . b )) by A10,CARD_5:2;
reconsider b as Ordinal by A11;
A12: ( succ b ) in ( dom f ) by A6,A8,A11,ORDINAL1:28;
then A13: ((( f . b ) = F(b) & ( f . ( succ b ) ) = F(( succ b ))) & P[ ( succ b ) ]) by A7,A8,A11;
F(b) c= F(( succ b )) by A2,ORDINAL3:1,ORDINAL4:27;
then ( succ d ) in ( f . ( succ b ) ) by A13,A11,ORDINAL1:28,ORDINAL3:8;
hence ( succ d ) in ( exp (a,c) ) by A10,A12,CARD_5:2;
end;
hence P[ c ] by ORDINAL1:28;
end;
P[ c ] from ORDINAL2:sch 1(A3,A4,A5);
hence thesis by A1;
end;
